DOCUMENT();

loadMacros(
  "PGstandard.pl",
  "MathObjects.pl",
  "PGML.pl",
  "PCCmacros.pl",
  "PGcourse.pl",
);


##############################################
TEXT(beginproblem());

##############################################

$fname = RandomVariableName(type=>function);  #get a name for the function
          


Context("Numeric");
$a = non_zero_random(-10,10,1);
$b = non_zero_random(-10,10,1);

$c = non_zero_random(1,10,1);

$den = Formula("x**2 +$c")->reduce;
$f = Formula("($a x + $b)/$den")->reduce;

Context("Interval");
Context()->flags->set(showExtraParens=>0,formatStudentAnswer=>'parsed');
$domain = Interval("(-inf,inf)");

##############################################



BEGIN_PGML
Find the domain of [``[$fname]``] where [``[$fname](x)=[$f]``].

[@KeyboardInstructions('Answer using interval notation. If you need to enter [`\infty`], you can type  [|inf|]* or  [|infinity|]*.  If you need to union two (or more) intervals, use the letter [|U|]*.  For example, to enter [`(\infty,5)\cup(5,10]`] you can type [|(-inf,5) U (5,10]|]*.')@]**

    [_____________]{$domain}

END_PGML

##############################################

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION

Since we are not allowed to divide by zero, the denominator of [``[$fname]``] cannot be zero. To find what [`x`] values will make the denominator zero, we solve the equation:

[``
\begin{aligned}
   [$den] &= 0 \\
   x^{2} &= [$c*-1] \\
\end{aligned}
``]

This equation has no real solutions, because a number squared cannot be negative. Since no number will make the denominator zero, the domain of [`[$fname]`] is:

     [`` [$domain] ``]

We could also say the domain is *all real numbers*.

END_PGML_SOLUTION








